<td>December</td>
<td>5, 12, 19, 26</td>
<td>49–52</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>January of next year</td>
<td>2, 9, 16, 23, 30</td>
<td>-</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>February of next year</td>
<td>6, 13, 20, 27</td>
<td>-</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>* In leap years the <i>n</i>th Doomsday is in <a href="/wiki/ISO_week_date" title="ISO week date">ISO week</a> <i>n</i>. In common years the day after the <i>n</i>th Doomsday is in week <i>n</i>. Thus in a common year the week number on the Doomsday itself is one less if it is a Sunday, i.e., in a <a href="/wiki/Common_year_starting_on_Friday" title="Common year starting on Friday">common year starting on Friday</a>.</p>
<p><a name="Formula_for_the_Doomsday_of_a_year" id="Formula_for_the_Doomsday_of_a_year"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Doomsday_rule&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Formula for the Doomsday of a year">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Formula for the Doomsday of a year</span></h2>
<p>For computer use the following formulas for the Doomsday of a year are convenient.</p>
<p>For the Gregorian calendar:</p>
<dl>
<dd><img class="tex" alt="\mbox{Doomsday} =  \mbox{Tuesday} + y + \left\lfloor\frac{y}{4}\right\rfloor - \left\lfloor\frac{y}{100}\right\rfloor + \left\lfloor\frac{y}{400}\right\rfloor" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/1/c/91c474fd8d3f801ad49364df935f8582.png" /></dd>
</dl>
<p>For the Julian calendar:</p>
<dl>
<dd><img class="tex" alt="\mbox{Doomsday} =  \mbox{Sunday} + y + \left\lfloor\frac{y}{4}\right\rfloor" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/0/7/607d3e92714cc7002644de7019e2c371.png" /></dd>
</dl>
<p>The formulas apply also for the <a href="/wiki/Proleptic_Gregorian_calendar" title="Proleptic Gregorian calendar">proleptic Gregorian calendar</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Proleptic_Julian_calendar" title="Proleptic Julian calendar">proleptic Julian calendar</a>. They use the <a href="/wiki/Floor_function" title="Floor function" class="mw-redirect">floor function</a> and <a href="/wiki/Astronomical_year_numbering" title="Astronomical year numbering">astronomical year numbering</a> for years BC.</p>
<p>For comparison, see <a href="/wiki/Julian_day#Calculation" title="Julian day">the calculation of a Julian day number</a>.</p>
<p><a name="Cycle" id="Cycle"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Doomsday_rule&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Cycle">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Cycle</span></h2>
